description:
File: rust/lichen-schc/src/codec.rs
Lines: 870-878 (in compress function), 415-456 (compress_rpl_dao)

Category: PROTOCOL

The compress function checks the D flag (DODAGID present) before calling compress_rpl_dao:
```rust
} else if icmp_code == 2 && packet.len() >= 40 + 4 + 20 {
    // DAO — only rule 4 if D flag set
    let kd_flags = packet[45];
    if kd_flags & 0x40 != 0 {
        if let Ok(n) = compress_rpl_dao(packet, out) {
            return Ok(n);
        }
    }
}
```

However, compress_rpl_dao itself does not verify the D flag. If called directly (bypassing compress()), it will compress DAO packets without DODAGID, but the compressed format still includes a 128-bit DODAGID field, reading garbage from rpl[4..20].

The decompressor (decompress_rpl_dao) also has no way to know if the D flag was set - it always reconstructs with D=1 based on kd_flags from the wire.

Impact: Direct calls to compress_rpl_dao() with D=0 packets produce corrupt compressed data. The public API is compress() which has the check, but compress_rpl_dao is fn (private but could be made pub).

Fix: Add D flag validation inside compress_rpl_dao:
```rust
let kd_flags = rpl[1];
if kd_flags & 0x40 == 0 {
    return Err(SchcError::NoMatchingRule);
}
```
